    std::vector<int> arr = {10, 7, 8, 9, 1, 5};

    std::cout << "Original array: ";
    printArray(arr);

    // Call Recursive Quicksort
    quicksortRecursive(arr, 0, arr.size() - 1);
    std::cout << "Sorted array (Recursive): ";
    printArray(arr);

    // Reset array for iterative sort
    arr = {10, 7, 8, 9, 1, 5};

    // Call Iterative Quicksort
    quicksortIterative(arr);
    std::cout << "Sorted array (Iterative): ";
    printArray(arr);

    return 0;
}
```

### Time Complexity Analysis:

1. **Best Case**: O(n log n)
   - This occurs when the pivot divides the array into two equal halves at every step.

2. **Average Case**: O(n log n)
   - On average, the pivot will divide the array into reasonably balanced partitions.

3. **Worst Case**: O(n)
   - This can happen when the pivot is the smallest or largest element repeatedly (e.g., when the array is already sorted or reverse sorted). The randomized pivot helps mitigate this issue significantly.

### Space Complexity:
- **Recursive Implementation**: O(log n) due to call stack space in the best case; O(n) in the worst case due to call stack space in unbalanced partitions.
- **Iterative Implementation**: O(n) due to the stack used to hold indices for traversal.

