```java
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;

public static String[] findAnagrams(String[] lexemes) {
    if (lexemes == null || lexemes.length < 2) {
        return new String[0];
    }

    Map<String, List<String>> anagramGroups = new HashMap<>();

    for (String lexeme : lexemes) {
        if (lexeme == null) continue;

        char[] chars = lexeme.toCharArray();
        Arrays.sort(chars);
        String sorted = new String(chars);

        anagramGroups.computeIfAbsent(sorted, k -> new ArrayList<>()).add(lexeme);
    }

    List<String> result = new ArrayList<>();
    for (List<String> group : anagramGroups.values()) {
        if (group.size() >= 2) {
            result.addAll(group);
        }
    }

    return result.toArray(new String[0]);
}
```

This solution:
1. Uses a HashMap to group lexemes by their sorted character sequences
2. Skips null values in the input array
3. Only returns lexemes that have at least one anagram in the input array
4. Maintains O(n) space complexity and O(n*k log k) time complexity (where n is number of lexemes and k is average length)
5. Preserves the original order of lexemes within their anagram groups
6. Returns an empty array if no anagrams are found or input is invalid

