Here's a Java subroutine that computes the standard deviation of an array of floating-point values:

```java
public class StandardDeviationCalculator {
    public static float calculateStandardDeviation(float[] data) {
        if (data == null || data.length == 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Input array cannot be null or empty");
        }

        // Calculate mean (average)
        float sum = 0.0f;
        for (float num : data) {
            sum += num;
        }
        float mean = sum / data.length;

        // Calculate the sum of squared differences from mean
        float squaredDiffSum = 0.0f;
        for (float num : data) {
            squaredDiffSum += (num - mean) * (num - mean);
        }

        // Calculate variance and standard deviation
        float variance = squaredDiffSum / data.length;
        float standardDeviation = (float) Math.sqrt(variance);

        return standardDeviation;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        float[] data = {3.3f, 5.6f, 7.8f, 5.4f, 9.9f};
        float result = calculateStandardDeviation(data);
        System.out.printf("Standard Deviation: %.4f%n", result);
    }
}
```

This code:
1. Calculates the mean (average) of the numbers
2. Computes the squared differences from the mean for each number
3. Calculates the variance (average of squared differences)
4. Returns the square root of the variance (standard deviation)

